Git Config is how you set up Git on your computer.


It tells Git important information like:

  Your name

  Your email

  Your default branch name

  Your code editor


The first thing beginners usually set is:

  user.name

  user.email



Git needs your name and email because every time you make a commit, Git labels it with who made the change.

  A commit is like a saved checkpoint in your project.

  So when you save your code, Git can show:

    Andrew made this change.

This is important when working alone, but it is even more important when working with other people.


  git config --global user.name "your_name"

  git config --global user.email "you@example.com"

To check name and email of your git we use this:

  git config --list


Git Config has different levels.

That means Git settings can apply to:

  Local: Only applies to the current project                  git config user.name "Project Name"
  
  Global: Applies to all your projects                        git config --global user.name "Andrew"
  
  System: Applies to every user on the computer:              git config --system user.name "System Name"

Different levels let you choose how wide the setting should apply.















